# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: colorado
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:colorado/100th-meridian-west] The **meridian 100° west** of the Prime Meridian of Greenwich is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, North America, the Pacific Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:colorado/100th-meridian-west] The 100th meridian west forms a great circle with the 80th meridian east.
[src:colorado/100th-meridian-west] In the United States, this meridian roughly marks the boundary between the semi-arid climate in the west and the humid continental and humid subtropical climates in the east, and as such roughly connotes the regions of the Eastern and the Western United States.
[src:colorado/100th-meridian-west] In the United States the meridian 100° west of Greenwich forms the eastern border of the Texas panhandle with Oklahoma (which traces its origin to the Adams-Onís Treaty in 1819 which settled the border between New Spain and the United States between the Red River and Arkansas River).
[src:colorado/100th-meridian-west] Dodge City, Kansas lies exactly at the intersection of the Arkansas River and the 100th meridian.
[src:colorado/100th-meridian-west] As first noted by John Wesley Powell in the 1870s, there is a big difference in rainfall by the different sides of the meridian.
[src:colorado/100th-meridian-west] West of the meridian, raising livestock is much more economically important than east of it, and what agriculture does exist relies heavily on irrigation.
[src:colorado/100th-meridian-west] Historically, the meridian has often been taken as a rough boundary between the eastern and western United States.
[src:colorado/100th-meridian-west] White settlement, spreading westward after the American Civil War, settled the area around this meridian during the 1870s.
[src:colorado/100th-meridian-west] Highway 30 in Cozad, Nebraska, marks the place where the 100th meridian intersects with the routes of the Oregon Trail, Pony Express, transcontinental railroad, and the Lincoln Highway.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The **10th Mountain Division (Light Infantry)** is a light infantry division in the United States Army based at Fort Drum, New York.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Formerly designated as a mountain warfare unit, the division was the only one of its size in the U.S. military to receive specialized training for fighting in mountainous conditions.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Originally activated as the **10th Light Division (Alpine)** in 1943, the division was redesignated the 10th Mountain Division in 1944 and fought in the mountains of Italy in some of the roughest terrain in World War II.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 5 May 1945, the division reached Nauders, Austria, just beyond the Reschen Pass, where it made contact with German s being pushed south by the U.S.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] A status quo was maintained until the enemy headquarters involved had completed their surrender to the Seventh.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 6 May, 10th Mountain troops met the 44th Infantry Division of Seventh Army.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Following the war, the division was deactivated, only to be reactivated and redesignated as the **10th Infantry Division** in 1948.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division first acted as a training division and, in 1954, was converted to a full combat division and, in 1955, was sent to Germany before being deactivated again in 1958.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Reactivated again in 1985, the division was designated the 10th Mountain Division (Light Infantry) to historically tie it to the World War II division and to also better describe its modern disposition.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Since its reactivation, the division or elements of the division have deployed numerous times.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Since 2001, the 10th Mountain Division has been the most deployed unit in the entire US military.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Its combat brigades have seen over 30 deployments, to both Iraq and Afghanistan, in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom and Operation Enduring Freedom, as well as Syria and parts of Africa in support of Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In November 1939, two months after World War II broke out in Europe, during the Soviet Union's invasion of Finland, Red Army efforts were frustrated following the destruction of two armored divisions by Finnish soldiers on skis.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The conflict caught attention as the outnumbered and outgunned Finnish soldiers were able to use the difficult local terrain to their advantage, severely hampering the Soviet attacks and embarrassing their military.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Upon seeing the effectiveness of these troops, Charles Minot "Minnie" Dole, the president of the National Ski Patrol, began to lobby the War Department of the need for a similar unit of troops in the United States Army, trained for fighting in winter and mountain warfare.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In September 1940, Dole was able to present his case to General George C.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Marshall, the Army Chief of Staff, who agreed with Dole's assessment, deciding to create a "Mountain" unit for fighting in harsh terrain.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army authorized the formation of the platoon-sized Army Ski Patrol in November 1940.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The first Patrol was formed at Camp Murray as part of the 41st Infantry Division under Lt.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Phelps (later to become commanding General of the 41st).
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The army, prompted by fears that its standing would not perform well in the event of a winter attack on the Northeastern coast, as well as knowledge that the German Army already had three mountain warfare divisions known as Gebirgsjäger, approved the concept for a division.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] This required an overhaul of U.S. military doctrine, as the concept of winter warfare had not been tested in the army since 1914.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] At first, planners envisioned ten mountain divisions, but personnel shortages revised the goal to three.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Eventually, the 10th Mountain Division would be the only one brought to active duty.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Italian military had lost a disastrous 25,000 men in the campaign because of their lack of preparedness to fight in the mountains.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 22 October 1941, General Marshall decided to form the first battalion of mountain warfare troops for a new mountain division.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Ski Patrol would assist in its training.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] It was the first mountain warfare unit in U.S. military history.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The National Ski Patrol took on the unique role of recruiting for the 87th Infantry Regiment and later the division, becoming the only civilian recruiting agency in military history.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army planners favored recruiting experienced skiers for the unit instead of trying to train standing troops in mountain warfare, so Dole recruited from schools, universities, and ski clubs for the unit.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 87th trained in harsh conditions, including Mount Rainier's 14,411-foot (4,392 m) peak, throughout 1942 as more recruits were brought in to form the division.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Initial training was conducted by Olympian Rolf Monsen.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] A new garrison was built for the division in central Colorado at Camp Hale, at an elevation of 9,200 feet (2,800 m) above sea level.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The **10th Light Division (Alpine)** was constituted on 10 July 1943 and activated five days later at Camp Hale under the command of Brigadier General Lloyd E.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Culin Jr. assigned as his assistant division commander (ADC).
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Light Division was centered on regimental commands; the 85th, 86th, and 87th Infantry Regiments.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division faced many difficulties in the new training, which had no established army doctrine.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Light Division was unique in that it was the only division in the army with three field artillery battalions instead of four.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] It was equipped with vehicles specialized in snow operation, such as the M29 Weasel, and winter weather gear, such as white camouflage and skis specifically designed for the division.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division practiced its rock climbing skills in preparation for the invasion of Italy on the challenging peaks of Seneca Rocks in West Virginia.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Its specialized training culminated with what were known as the "D-Series" ("D" for "Divisional"), military maneuvers on the divisional level in the Colorado Rockies in Winter conditions.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Beginning 26 March 1944, the exercises were intended to last five weeks.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The soldiers endured an adverse environment, and "tactical conditions" that banned open fires in sub-zero temperatures.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] As a result, the exercises were ended after 3 weeks.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Official statistics recorded 195 cases of frostbite and 340 other incapacitating injuries.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 22 June 1944, the division was shipped to Camp Swift, Texas, to prepare for maneuvers in Louisiana, which were later canceled.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] A period of acclimation to a low altitude and hot climate was thought necessary to prepare for this training.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 6 November 1944, the 10th Division was redesignated the **10th Mountain Division**.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] That same month, the blue and white "Mountain" tab was authorized for the division's new shoulder sleeve insignia.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Also in November, the division received a new commander, Brigadier General George Price Hays, a Medal of Honor recipient and a distinguished veteran of World War I.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On January 4, 1945, he received a promotion to major general.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division sailed for the Italian front in two parts, with the 86th Infantry and support leaving Camp Patrick Henry, Virginia on 11 December 1944 aboard the SS *Argentina* and arriving in Naples, Italy on 22 December.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 85th and 87th Infantry left Hampton Roads, Virginia on 4 January 1945 aboard the SS *West Point* and arrived on 13 January 1945.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 6 January, its support units were preparing to head to the front lines.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] It was attached to Major General Willis D.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Crittenberger's IV Corps, part of the American Fifth Army, commanded by Lieutenant General Lucian Truscott.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 8 January, the 86th Infantry had moved to Bagni di Lucca near Mount Belvedere in preparation for an offensive by the Fifth Army to capture the mountain along with surrounding high ground, which allowed the Axis to block advances to Po Valley.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Starting 14 January, the division began moving to Pisa as part of the Fifth Army massing for this attack.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 20 January, all three of the 10th's regiments were on or near the front line between the Serchio Valley and Mt.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Barlow commanded the 85th Regiment, Col.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] While the Brazilian division was in charge of taking Monte Castello and *Castelnuovo* di Vergato, the 10th Mountain Division was responsible for the Mount Belvedere area, climbing nearby Riva Ridge during the night of 18 February and attacking Mount della Torraccia on 20 February.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] These peaks were cleared after four days of heavy fighting, as Axis troops launched several counterattacks in these positions.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In early March, the division fought its way north of Canolle and moved to within 15 miles (24 km) of Bologna.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 5 March, while Brazilian units captured Castelnuovo, the 85th and the 87th Infantry took respectively Mount Della Spe and Castel D'Aiano, cutting the Axis routes of resupply and communication into the Po Valley, setting the stage for the next Fifth Army offensive.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division maintained defensive positions in this area for three weeks, anticipating a counteroffensive by the German s.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In the final days of April 1945, as German defenses in northern Italy collapsed, the 10th Mountain Division advanced north toward Lake Garda in pursuit of retreating s.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The difficult terrain and destroyed infrastructure around the lake required the use of amphibious DUKW vehicles for transport and assault.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On the night of 30 April, one such vehicle carrying 25 soldiers sank during the crossing, resulting in one of the last and most tragic losses of the Italian campaign.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] That same day, the division's newly appointed Assistant Commander, Colonel William Orlando Darby—founder of the U.S.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army Rangers—was killed by artillery fire in Torbole, together with Sergeant Major John T.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The events at Lake Garda marked the final combat actions for the 10th Mountain Division in Europe and have since become a lasting symbol of the cost of liberation.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Their story, long preserved by veterans and local historians, was later chronicled through research and documentary projects led by Italian and American collaborators, including Associazione Benàch and the 2023 film *The Lost Mountaineers*.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division resumed its attack on 14 April 1945, pressing forward on multiple axes.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] That day it assaulted Torre Iussi and Rocca Roffeno, north of Mount Della Spe.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] After stiff fighting, on 17 April it broke through the German Gothic Line defenses, opening the way into the Po Valley.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Over the next days the advance continued: on 20 April the 10th captured Mongiorgio and pushed into the Po plain, taking key positions at Pradalbino and Bomporto.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division crossed the Po River at San Benedetto Po on 23 April, reached Verona on 25 April, and encountered heavy resistance in the areas of Torbole and Nago.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Because the routes around Lake Garda had been rendered impassable by destroyed tunnels and bridges, the division carried out an amphibious crossing of the lake using DUKW vehicles.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 30 April it secured Gargnano and Porto di Tremosine on the western shore, effectively ending organized German resistance in northern Italy.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] That same night, however, a tragic accident occurred.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] During a night operation to transport troops and equipment across Lake Garda from Torbole toward the northern shore, one DUKW carrying 25 men of the 10th Mountain Division sank in deep water during rough weather.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The vehicle, heavily loaded with men, a 75 mm pack howitzer, ammunition, and gear, began taking on water and foundered before rescue could reach it.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Hough, survived; the others were declared Missing in Action (MIA) and remain unaccounted for.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The site of the sinking remained unknown for decades, despite repeated efforts by the U.S.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army, local divers, and underwater archaeology teams.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2012, after several unsuccessful surveys, the Italian volunteer rescue group Volontari del Garda located the wreck upright on the lakebed using sonar and remotely operated vehicles.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The ongoing research and commemorative work were later supported by the Italian historical association Associazione Benàch, which collaborated with local authorities and U.S. veterans’ families to preserve the memory of the missing soldiers.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 2023 documentary *The Lost Mountaineers*, produced by the Fondazione Museo Storico del Trentino in collaboration with Associazione Benàch, chronicles these final days of combat and the search for the lost soldiers.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The film reconstructs the events leading to the sinking, the experiences of the men aboard, and the decades-long recovery efforts.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] It also situates the tragedy within the wider story of the 10th Mountain Divisions campaign in northern Italy and its human cost.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On the same day, 30 April 1945, the division also suffered the loss of its Assistant Division Commander, Colonel William O.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] While in Torbole on the northern shore of Lake Garda, Darby was killed by an enemy artillery shell explosion along with his Sergeant Major, John T.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Darby had been appointed to the division only days earlier, following the wounding of Brigadier General Robinson E.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Duff, and was directing the final movements of the divisions advance when he was struck by shrapnel.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] His death came just hours before the announcement of the German surrender in Italy.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] After the German capitulation on 2 May 1945, the division shifted to security and occupation duties.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 5 May it reached Nauders, Austria, just beyond the Reschen Pass, where it linked up with elements of the U.S.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Between 2 May and Victory in Europe Day (8 May), the 10th Mountain Division accepted the surrender of German units and secured key areas in northeastern Italy and western Slovenia.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 20 May it had redeployed to Udine, joining the British Eighth Army to prevent further westward movement of Yugoslav troops.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In July, the Department of War assigned the 10th Mountain to the Pacific theater; after a month's furlough the men would assemble at Camp Carson, where they would train for Operation Downfall, the invasion of mainland Japan.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Between 26 July and 2 August the three regiments boarded ships for the return voyage to the United States; the day before the first of these regiments, the 86th Mountain Infantry, disembarked at Hampton Roads, Hiroshima was leveled by an atom bomb.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Three days after the rest of the division landed stateside on 11 August, Japan officially surrendered.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division was demobilized and inactivated on 30 November 1945 at Camp Carson, Colorado.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] During World War II, the 10th Mountain Division suffered 992 killed in action and 4,154 wounded in action in 114 days of combat.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Soldiers of the division were awarded one Medal of Honor (John D.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Magrath), three Distinguished Service Crosses, one Distinguished Service Medal, 449 Silver Star Medals, seven Legion of Merit Medals, 15 Soldier's Medals, and 7,729 Bronze Star Medals.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division itself was awarded two campaign streamers.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In June 1948, the division was rebuilt and activated at Fort Riley, Kansas to serve as a training division.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Without its "Mountain" tab, the division served as the 10th Infantry Division for the next ten .
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The unit was charged with processing and training replacements in large numbers.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] This mission was expanded with the outbreak of the Korean War in 1950.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 1953, the division had trained 123,000 new Army recruits at Fort Riley.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 1954, the division was converted to a combat division once again, though it did not regain its "Mountain" status.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Using equipment from the deactivating 37th Infantry Division, the **10th Infantry Division** was deployed to Germany in 1955, replacing the 1st Infantry Division at Würzburg, serving as part of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) defensive .
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division served in Germany for four , until it was rotated out and replaced by the 3rd Infantry Division.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division moved to Fort Benning, Georgia, and was inactivated on 14 June 1958.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 13 February 1985, the 10th Mountain Division (Light Infantry) was reactivated at Fort Drum, New York.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In accordance with the Reorganization Objective Army Divisions plan, the division was no longer centered on regiments, instead two brigades were activated under the division.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 1st Brigade, 10th Mountain Division (commanded by then Colonel John M.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Keane, later 4-Star General and Army Vice Chief of Staff) and Division Artillery were activated at Fort Drum, while the 2nd Brigade, 10th Mountain Division was activated at Fort Benning, moving to Fort Drum in 1988.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division was also assigned a round-out brigade from the Army National Guard, the 27th Infantry Brigade.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division was specially designed as a light infantry division able to rapidly deploy.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In this process, it lost its mountain warfare capability, but its light infantry organization still made it versatile for difficult terrain.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Equipment design was oriented toward reduced size and weight for reasons of both strategic and tactical mobility.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division also received a distinctive unit insignia.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 1990, the division sent 1,200 soldiers to support Operation Desert Storm.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Two infantry platoons from the division were among those sent: 1st Platoon Bravo Company 1/22 and the 1/22 Scout Platoon.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Once in Iraq, the scouts were sent home and First Platoon was left as a counterintelligence .
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Performing three-man 24hr patrols through the remainder of their deployment, this platoon was widely regarded as the division's best at that time.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Following a cease-fire in March 1991, the support soldiers began redeploying to Fort Drum through June of that year.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Hurricane Andrew struck South Florida on 24 August 1992, killing 13 people, leaving another 250,000 homeless, and causing damages in excess of $20 billion.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 27 August 1992, the 10th Mountain Division assumed responsibility for Hurricane Andrew disaster relief as Task Mountain.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Division soldiers set up relief camps, distributed food, clothing, medical necessities, and building supplies, as well as helping to homes and clear debris.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The last of the 6,000 division soldiers deployed to Florida returned home in October 1992.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 3 December 1992, the division headquarters was designated as the headquarters for all Army s (ARFOR) of the Unified Task (UNITAF) for Operation Restore Hope.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Arnold, the division Commander, was named Army s commander.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division's mission was to secure major cities and roads to provide safe passage of relief supplies to the Somali population suffering from the effects of the Somali Civil War.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Due to 10th Mountain Division efforts, humanitarian agencies declared an end to the food emergency and factional fighting decreased.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] When Task Ranger and the SAR team were pinned down during a raid in what later became known as the Battle of Mogadishu, the 10th Mountain Division provided infantry for the UN quick reaction sent to rescue them.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division had two soldiers killed in the fighting, which was the longest sustained firefight by regular U.S.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division began a gradual reduction of s in Somalia in February 1994, until the last soldiers of the 2nd Battalion, 22nd Infantry returned to the United States in March 1994.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division formed the nucleus of the Multinational Haiti (MNF Haiti) and Joint Task 190 (JTF 190) in Haiti during Operation Uphold Democracy.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] More than 8,600 of the division's troops deployed during this operation.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 19 September 1994, the 1st Brigade conducted the Army's first air assault from aircraft carrier USS *Dwight D.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] This consisted of 54 helicopters and almost 2,000 soldiers.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] They occupied the Port-au-Prince International Airport.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] This was the largest Army air operation conducted from a carrier since the Doolittle Raid in World War II.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division's mission was to create a secure and stable environment so the government of Haitian President Jean-Bertrand Aristide could be reestablished and democratic s held.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] After this was accomplished, the 10th Mountain Division handed over control of the MNF-Haiti to the 25th Infantry Division on 15 January 1995.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division redeployed the last of its soldiers who served in Haiti by 31 January 1995.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In the fall of 1998, the division received notice that it would be serving as senior headquarters of Task Eagle, providing a peacekeeping to support the ongoing operation within the Multi-National Division-North area of responsibility in Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Selected division units began deploying in late summer, approximately 3,000 division soldiers deployed.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] After performing their mission in Bosnia, the division units conducted a transfer of authority, relinquishing their assignments to soldiers of the 49th Armored Division, Texas National Guard.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] By early summer 2000, all 10th Mountain Division soldiers had returned safely to Fort Drum.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] During the 2000 presidential , the readiness of the 10th Mountain Division became a political issue when George W.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Bush asserted that the division was "not ready for duty." He attributed the division's low readiness to the frequent deployments throughout the 1990s without time in between for division elements to retrain and refit.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] General Accounting Office in July 2000 also noted that although the entire 10th Mountain Division was not deployed to the contingencies at once, "deployment of key components—especially headquarters—makes these divisions unavailable for deployment elsewhere in case of a major war".
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Conservative think tank The Heritage Foundation agreed with these sentiments, charging that the U.S. military overall was not prepared for war due to post–Cold War drawdowns of the U.S. military.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Army responded that, though the 10th Mountain Division had been unprepared following its deployment as Task Eagle, that the unit was fully prepared for combat by late 2000 despite being undermanned.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Still, the Army moved the 10th Mountain Division down on the deployment list, allowing it time to retrain and refit.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2002, columnist and highly decorated military veteran David Hackworth again criticized the 10th Mountain Division for being unprepared due to lack of training, low physical fitness, unprepared leadership, and low morale.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] He said the division was no longer capable of mountain warfare.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] These concerns were quickly debunked as the 10th Mountain Division was the first conventional unit in the entire US military to be deployed to Afghanistan, seeing heavy combat.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Following the 11 September 2001 attacks, elements of the division, including its special troops battalion and 1st Battalion, 87th Infantry Regiment (1-87th) infantry deployed to Afghanistan as part of Operation Enduring Freedom in late 2001.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] This was the first conventional unit to be deployed in the entire US military.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division headquarters arrived at Karshi-Khanabad Air Base, under Major General Franklin L.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Hagenbeck, on 12 December 2001 to function as the Combined s Land Component Command (CFLCC) (Forward).
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] This command served as the representative for Lieutenant General Paul T.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army/CFLCC commanding general (CG) in the theater of operations.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division was also intended to defend Uzbekistan against attacks by the Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan, which was seeking to overthrow Islam Karimov's secular government.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 13 February 2002, Mikolashek ordered Hagenbeck to move CFLCC (Forward) to Bagram airfield located at Bagram and 2 days later the headquarters was officially redesignated as Combined Joint Task (CJTF) Mountain.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] It assumed responsibility for the planning and execution of what had then become known as Operation Anaconda.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Elements of the division, primarily 1-87th Infantry, remained in the country until mid-2002, fighting to secure remote areas of the country and participating in prominent operations such as Operation Anaconda, the Fall of Mazar-i-Sharif, and the Battle of Qala-i-Jangi.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] These 1-87th Infantry soldiers became the first U.S. conventional s to fight in Afghanistan.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division also participated in fighting in the Shahi Khot Valley in 2002.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In June 2002, elements of the 82nd Airborne Division arrived to relieve CJTF Mountain, and in September, Major General John R.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Vines and his Combined Task 82 relieved CJTF Mountain as the major subordinate headquarters to Combined Joint Task 180.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Upon the return of the battalions, they were welcomed home and praised by President Bush.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2003, the division's headquarters, along with the 1st Brigade, returned to Afghanistan.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] During that time, they operated in the frontier regions of the country such as Paktika Province, going to places previously untouched by the war in search of Taliban and Al-Qaeda s.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Fighting in several small-scale conflicts such as Operation Avalanche, Operation Mountain Resolve, and Operation Mountain Viper, the division maintained a strategy of small units moving through remote regions of the country to interact directly with the population and drive out insurgents.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 1st Brigade also undertook a number of humanitarian missions.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2003 and into 2004, the division's aviation brigade deployed for the first time to Afghanistan.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] As the only aviation brigade in the theater, the brigade provided air support for all U.S.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade's mission at that time focused on close air support, medevac missions, and other duties involving combat with Taliban and Al-Qaeda s in the country.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division was the first unit to introduce contract working dogs into southern Afghanistan.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In the spring of 2004, they had Patriot K-9 Services supply 20 dog teams based at KAF.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The teams were trained to detect explosives and perform patrol duties throughout the region.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade returned to Fort Drum in 2004.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On the return of the division headquarters and 1st Brigade, the 10th Mountain Division began the process of transformation into a modular division.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 16 September 2004, the division headquarters finished its transformation, adding the 10th Mountain Division Special Troops Battalion.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 1st Brigade became the 1st Brigade Combat Team, while the 3rd Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division was activated for the first time.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In January 2005, the 4th Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division was activated at Fort Polk, Louisiana.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] 2nd Brigade Combat Team would not be transformed until September 2005, pending a deployment to Iraq.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In late 2004, the 2nd Brigade Combat Team was deployed to Iraq supporting Operation Iraqi Freedom.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 2nd Brigade Combat Team undertook combat operations in western Baghdad, an area of responsibility that included Abu Ghraib, Mansour, and Route Irish.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Around that time, the 1st Brigade Combat Team deployed back to Iraq, staying in the country until 2006.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The next time the 1st Brigade Combat Team was deployed was during the Surge for 15 months in Iraq.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Northern Iraq was the theater of operations for 1 BCT from August 2007 until November 2008.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 4th BCT operated in Northeast Baghdad under the 4th Infantry Division headquarters from November 2007 until January 2009.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain participated in larger-scale operations, such as Operation Phantom Phoenix.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] After a one-year rest, the headquarters of the 10th Mountain Division was deployed to Iraq for the first time in April 2008.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division headquarters transferred authority for MND-S to the 34th Infantry Division, Minnesota Army National Guard on 20 May 2009.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 2nd Brigade Combat Team was scheduled to deploy to Iraq in the fall of 2009, as a part of the 2009–2010 rotation to Iraq.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division headquarters, the 3rd Brigade Combat Team, and two Battalion Task s from the 4th Brigade Combat Team deployed to Afghanistan in 2005, staying in the country until 2006.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division and brigade served in the eastern region of the country, along the border with Pakistan, fulfilling a similar role as it did during its previous deployment.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] During this time, the deployment of the brigade was extended along with that of the 4th Brigade, 82nd Airborne Division.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] It was eventually replaced by the 173rd Airborne Brigade Combat Team which was rerouted from Iraq.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In the winter of 2006, the 10th Aviation Brigade, 10th Mountain Division, was deployed again to Afghanistan to support Operation Enduring Freedom as the only aviation brigade in the theater, stationed at Bagram Air Base, Afghanistan.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Named "Task Falcon," the brigade's mission was to conduct aviation operations to destroy insurgents and anti-coalition militia in an effort to help build the Afghan National Security 's capability and allow the Afghan government to increase its capabilities.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In addition, the Task provided logistical and combat support for International Security Assistance s throughout the country.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 3rd Brigade Combat Team was slated to deploy to Iraq in 2009, but that deployment was rerouted.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In January 2009, the 3rd BCT instead deployed to Kunar, Logar and Wardak Provinces, eastern Afghanistan to relieve the 101st Airborne Division, as part of a new buildup of US s in that country.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade was responsible for expanding forward operating bases and combat outposts (COPs) in the region, as well as strengthening US military presence in preparation for additional US s to arrive.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 1st Brigade Combat Team was scheduled to deploy to Iraq in late 2009 but deployed instead to Afghanistan in March 2010 for 13 months.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] 1-87th Infantry deployed to Kunduz and Baghlan Provinces, establishing remote combat outposts (COPs) against the Taliban after they had taken control of these provinces over the last several .
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Notably, Blacksheep Company was responsible for numerous large-scale engagements, including the Battle of Shahabuddin and securing a High-Value Target (HVT) after an air assault raid.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] This deployment was transformational to the Counterinsurgency in Northern Afghanistan campaign of the war.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Brigade again deployed to Afghanistan in late 2012 to Ghazni Provence for nine months.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 3rd Brigade Combat Team deployed to Kandahar Province, southern Afghanistan in March 2011, again relieving the 101st Airborne Division.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] During this deployment, 3rd BCT mainly occupied forward operating bases (FOBs) and combat outposts (COPs) in the Maywand, Zhari, and Arghandab Districts of Kandahar Province.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade was redeployed to Fort Drum in March 2012 after a twelve-month deployment.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 4th Brigade Combat Team deployed to Regional Command East, under the 101st Airborne Division from October 2010 until their redeployment in October 2011.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 4th BCT deployed to both Wardak and Logar provinces.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] During this deployment, they went to places such as Chakh Valley in Wardak Province and Charkh Valley in Logar Province in search of elements of the Haqqani Network.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In May 2013, the brigade deployed again to Afghanistan returning home in February 2014.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 5 December 2019, the Department of the Army announced that the 1st Brigade Combat Team would replace the 3rd Brigade Combat Team, 82nd Airborne Division as part of a unit rotation in support of Operation Freedom's Sentinel.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade deployed to Afghanistan in February 2020.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 3 November 2016, *Stars and Stripes* reported that the 10th Combat Aviation Brigade would deploy 1,750 soldiers to Eastern Europe in March 2017, in support of Operation Atlantic Resolve – as part of NATO efforts to reassure Eastern Europe in response to Russian intervention in Ukraine in 2014.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade arrived with approximately 60 aircraft, including CH-47 Chinooks, UH-60 Blackhawks, and medevac helicopters.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade was headquartered in Germany and the brigade's units were forward-based at locations in Latvia, Romania, and Poland.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Between late summer and early fall 2015, as well as again in 2016, 1,250 soldiers from the 1st Brigade Combat Team were deployed to Iraq to support Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] During the two deployments the brigade spent in Iraq, they fought to regain control of the cities of Ramadi, Fallujah, and Mosul from the Islamic State of Iraq and Syria.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2022 the unit would redeploy again, in support of Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division was awarded two campaign streamers in World War II, one campaign streamer for Somalia, and four campaign streamers in the war on terrorism, for a total of seven campaign streamers and three unit decorations in its operational history.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Note that some of the division's brigades received more or fewer decorations depending on their individual deployments.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2026, the Army announced that it has officially approved the formerly unauthorized ski trooper insignia to be worn on the AGSU garrison cap for soldiers in the 10th Mountain Division.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Skiing associations subsequently contend that veterans of the 10th Mountain Division had a substantial effect on the post–World War II development of skiing as a vacation industry and major sport.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Ex-soldiers from the 10th laid out ski hills, designed ski lifts, became ski coaches, racers, instructors, patrollers, shop owners, and filmmakers.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] They wrote and published ski magazines, opened ski schools, improved ski equipment, and developed ski resorts.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Up to 2,000 of the division's troops were involved in skiing-related professions after the war, and at least 60 ski resorts were founded by men of the division.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] People associated with the 10th Mountain Division later went on to achieve notability in other fields.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Bill Bowerman, former executive director and Sierra Club leader David R.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Brower, former United States Ski Team member World War II civilian mountaineer trainer H.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Additionally, five members of the division have been awarded the Medal of Honor.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Magrath became the first member of the division to receive this award (posthumously) during World War II.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Monti, received it posthumously in 2009, for actions during a combat operation on 21 June 2006 in Afghanistan.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Swenson, received it in 2013, for actions on 8 September 2009, during the Battle of Ganjgal in Afghanistan.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] Atkins, received it posthumously on 27 March 2019, for actions on 1 June 2007 during a patrol in Iraq.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The fifth, Michael Ollis, received it posthumously on 2 March 2026, for actions on 28 August 2013 during an attack in Afghanistan.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division's efforts in Afghanistan during Operation Enduring Freedom and beyond led to the division being referred to as the "Tribe of Crossed Swords" by some Afghans.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division's first appearance in popular literature was the semi-fictional novel by Frank Harper, *Night Climb*, published in 1946 by Longsman, Green, and Company.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The title of this book came from the unit's celebrated night ascent of Riva Ridge as part of the Battle of Mount Belvedere, and the novel follows the actions of several members through Operation Encore and Operation Craftsman to the end of hostilities in Italy.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Division was later the subject of the 1996 film *Fire on the Mountain*, which documented its exploits during World War II.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division is also a prominent element of the book *Black Hawk Down* and film *by the same name*, which portrays the Battle of Mogadishu and the division's participation in that conflict.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p01] John, referencing his time spent with the 10th Mountain Division in Afghanistan.
[src:colorado/10th-mountain-division-p02] This division consists of a division headquarters and headquarters battalion, three infantry brigade combat teams, a division artillery, a combat aviation brigade, and a division sustainment brigade.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:colorado/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:colorado/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:colorado/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] The **1882 Fort Collins earthquake** or **Front Range earthquake** measured Mw 6.6 and struck near Fort Collins, Colorado at 1:30 UTC on November 8, which was 18:30 on the November 7.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] The earthquake occurred as the result of deformation within the Front Range and caused shaking as strong as Modified Mercalli intensity (MMI) VII (*Very Strong*).
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] Shaking was felt as far away as Salt Lake City, Utah and Salina, Kansas.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] An aftershock struck locally at 04:45 on November 8 and was felt as far as Laramie, Wyoming and Meeker, Colorado.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] It is the largest earthquake in Colorado's history.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] The Southern Rocky Mountains are still actively growing due to the Laramide orogeny.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] The Front Range accommodates some of this as a deformation front of the orogeny.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] Stresses in this region are generally northwest–southeast oriented.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] The causative fault of this specific earthquake is unknown, but other earthquakes such as the 1984 Wyoming earthquake struck at a depth of 20 km (12 mi).
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] The Mw 6.6 earthquake struck at 01:30 on November 8 in UTC time, or 18:30 on November 7.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] The earthquake caused Modified Mercalli intensity (MMI) VII (*Very Strong*) shaking in various localities near in the Front Range urban corridor and was felt over an area of 470,000 km2 (180,000 sq mi).
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] Due to the sparseness of the epicentral region, very little is known about where exactly the earthquake occurred.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] An aftershock of magnitude 4.5 to 5.0 was also felt in the urban corridor.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] This earthquake is the largest known to have occurred in the state of Colorado.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] At the University of Colorado Boulder, plaster fell from the ceiling.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] In Denver, some bolts snapped and bent at an electric light plant.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] In La Porte, a wooden house suffered cracking.
[src:colorado/1882-fort-collins-earthquake] At Thompson, a house's walls were severely cracked and the plaster on some walls came off.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The **1890 United States census** was taken beginning June 2, 1890.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The census determined the resident population of the United States to be 62,979,766, an increase of 25.5 percent over the 50,189,209 persons enumerated during the 1880 census.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The data reported that the distribution of the population had resulted in the disappearance of the American frontier.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a majority of states recorded populations of over one million and the first in which three cities, New York City, Chicago, and Philadelphia, recorded populations of over one million.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The census also saw Chicago rise in rank to the nation's second-most populous city, a position it would hold until Los Angeles, the 57th-most populous city as of 1890, supplanted it in 1990.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] This was the first U.S. census to use machines to tabulate the collected data.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] Most of the 1890 census materials were destroyed on January 10, 1921, when the Commerce Department building caught fire, and in the subsequent disposal of the remaining damaged records.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census was the first to be compiled using methods invented by Herman Hollerith and was overseen by Superintendents Robert P.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] Data was entered on a machine readable medium (punched cards) and tabulated by machine.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] Changes from the 1880 census included the larger population, the number of data items to be collected from individuals, the Census Bureau headcount, the volume of scheduled publications, and the use of Hollerith's electromechanical tabulators.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The net effect of these changes was to reduce the time required to process the census from eight years for the 1880 census to six years for the 1890 census.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The total population of 62,947,714, the family, or *rough*, count, was announced after only six weeks of processing (punched cards were not used for this tabulation).
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The public reaction to this tabulation was disbelief, as it was widely believed that the "right answer" was at least 75,000,000.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The United States census of 1890 showed a total of 248,253 Native Americans living in the United States, down from 400,764 Native Americans identified in the census of 1850.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census announced that the frontier region of the United States no longer existed, and that the Census Bureau would no longer track the westward migration of the U.S. population.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] In practice, however, said migration can still be tracked by plotting each succeeding census' mean center of United States population.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] By 1890, settlement in the American West had reached sufficient population density that the frontier line had disappeared.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The original data for the 1890 census is mostly unavailable.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The population schedules were damaged in a fire in the basement of the U.S.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] Department of Commerce building in Washington, D.C. in 1921.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] Some 25% of the materials were presumed destroyed and another 50% damaged by smoke and water, although the actual damage may have been closer to 15–25%.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The damage to the records led to an outcry for a permanent National Archives.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] In December 1932, following standard federal record-keeping procedures, the Chief Clerk of the Bureau of the Census sent the Librarian of Congress a list of papers to be destroyed, including the original 1890 census schedules.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] The Librarian was asked by the Bureau to identify any records which should be retained for historical purposes, but the Librarian did not accept the census records.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] Congress authorized destruction of that list of records on February 21, 1933, and the surviving original 1890 census records were destroyed by government order by 1934 or 1935.
[src:colorado/1890-united-states-census] Few sets of microdata from the 1890 census survive.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The region has been inhabited by Native Americans and their Paleo-Indian ancestors for at least 13,500 years and possibly much longer.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The eastern edge of the Rocky Mountains was a major migration route for early peoples who spread throughout the Americas.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In 1848, much of the Nuevo México region was annexed to the United States with the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Pike's Peak Gold Rush of 1858–1862 created an influx of settlers.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] On February 28, 1861, U.S. president James Buchanan signed an act creating the Territory of Colorado, and on August 1, 1876, president Ulysses S.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Grant signed Proclamation 230, admitting Colorado to the Union as the 38th state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Denver is the capital, the most populous city, and the center of the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Colorado Springs is the second-most populous city of the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Residents of the state are known as Coloradans, although the antiquated "Coloradoan" is occasionally used.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Colorado generally ranks as one of the top U.S. states for education attainment, employment, and healthcare quality.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Major parts of its economy include government and defense, mining, agriculture, tourism, and manufacturing.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] With increasing temperatures and decreasing water availability, Colorado's agriculture, forestry, and tourism economies are expected to be heavily affected by climate change.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The region that is today the State of Colorado has been inhabited by Native Americans and their Paleo-Indian ancestors for at least 13,500 years and possibly more than 37,000 years.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Lindenmeier site contains artifacts dating from approximately 8720 BCE.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Ancient Pueblo peoples lived in the valleys and mesas of the Colorado Plateau in far southwestern Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Ute Nation inhabited the mountain valleys of the Southern Rocky Mountains and the Western Rocky Mountains, even as far east as the Front Range of the present day.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Apache and the Comanche also inhabited the Eastern and Southeastern parts of the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In the 17th century, the Arapaho and Cheyenne moved west from the Great Lakes region to hunt across the High Plains of Colorado and Wyoming.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The U.S. acquired the territorial claim to the eastern Rocky Mountains with the Louisiana Purchase from France in 1803.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Army reconnaissance expedition into the disputed region.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Colonel Pike and his troops were arrested by Spanish cavalrymen in the San Luis Valley the following February, taken to Chihuahua, and expelled from Mexico the following July.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Under the 1819 Adams-Onís Treaty, the U.S. acquired Florida from Spain while relinquishing claims to lands west of the 100th meridian and south of both the Arkansas River and the 42nd parallel.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The treaty took effect on February 22, 1821.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Having settled its border with Spain, the U.S. admitted the southeastern portion of the Territory of Missouri to the Union as the state of Missouri on August 10, 1821.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The remainder of Missouri Territory, including what would become northeastern Colorado, became an unorganized territory and remained so for 33 years over the question of slavery.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] After 11 years of war, Spain finally recognized the independence of Mexico with the Treaty of Córdoba signed on August 24, 1821.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Mexico eventually ratified the Adams–Onís Treaty in 1831.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Texian Revolt of 1835–36 fomented a dispute between the U.S. and Mexico which eventually erupted into the Mexican–American War in 1846.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Mexico surrendered its northern territory to the U.S. with the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo after the war in 1848; this included much of the western and southern areas of Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Santa Fe Trail connected the Missouri River to Santa Fe, New Mexico, where it linked with the Camino Real de Tierra Adentro extending southward into Mexico.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Others traveling overland avoided the rugged Southern Rocky Mountains, and instead followed the North Platte River and Sweetwater River to South Pass (Wyoming), the lowest crossing of the Continental Divide between the Southern Rocky Mountains and the Central Rocky Mountains.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In 1849, the Mormons of the Salt Lake Valley organized the extralegal State of Deseret, claiming the entire Great Basin and all lands drained by the rivers Green, Grand, and Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The federal government of the U.S. flatly refused to recognize the new Mormon government because it was theocratic and sanctioned plural marriage.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Instead, the Compromise of 1850 divided the Mexican Cession and the northwestern claims of Texas into a new state and two new territories, the state of California, the Territory of New Mexico, and the Territory of Utah.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Provisional Government of the Territory of Jefferson was an extralegal and unrecognized United States territory that existed in the Pike's Peak mining region from October 24, 1859, until it yielded to the new Territory of Colorado on June 6, 1861.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Jefferson Territory included all of the present State of Colorado and portions of the present states of Kansas, Nebraska, Utah, and Wyoming.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The people were desirous of a closer government than those five territories provided.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The government of the Jefferson Territory, while democratically elected, was never legally recognized by the United States government, although it managed the territory with relatively free rein for 19 months.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Many of the laws enacted by the General Assembly of the Territory of Jefferson were reenacted and given official sanction by the new Colorado General Assembly in 1861.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Territory of Colorado was an organized incorporated territory of the United States that existed from February 28, 1861, until August 1, 1876, when it was admitted to the Union as the 38th State of Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The territory was created during the onset of the American Civil War in the wake of the Pike's Peak Gold Rush, which brought the first large concentration of settlers from the east to the region.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The war stifled growth, but following the war mining grew more industrialized and fueled the economy.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The construction of railroads further improved the economy.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The boundaries of the newly designated Colorado Territory were very similar to those of the modern State of Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In 1861 following the beginning of the American Civil War, there were several small disputes and skirmishes between confederate supporters and union supporters.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In August, Governor Gilpin organized the 1st Colorado Infantry.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Slough led the group to New Mexico Territory in February–March 1862.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] There they fought in the battles of Apache Canyon, Glorieta Pass and Peralta.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Slough resigned in April 1862 and was replaced by Major John M.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] With resources tied up in the war there was little left over for mines, farms, and infrastructure, and Denver stagnated.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] On March 26, 1862 John Evans was appointed by Abraham Lincoln as the second governor of the territory.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] He prompted investment in Denver rail projects, and founded the University of Denver in 1864.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Anti-native sentiment grew during the Civil War years.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Exterminationist ideology, led in Colorado by Evans and Chivington, advocated for the total eradication of all native people in the territory.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Colorado War worsened relations with natives until 1864 when Chivington ordered the Sand Creek Massacre and Evans was forced to resign the following spring.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In 1867, the Union Pacific Railroad laid its tracks west to Weir, now Julesburg, in the northeast corner of the Territory.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Union Pacific linked up with the Central Pacific Railroad at Promontory Summit, Utah, on May 10, 1869, to form the First transcontinental railroad.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Denver Pacific Railway reached Denver in June of the following year, and the Kansas Pacific arrived two months later to forge the second line across the continent.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The United States Congress passed an enabling act on March 3, 1875, specifying the requirements for the Territory of Colorado to become a state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] On August 1, 1876 (four weeks after the Centennial of the United States), U.S.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Grant signed a proclamation admitting Colorado to the Union as the 38th state and earning it the moniker "Centennial State".
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The discovery of a major silver lode near Leadville in 1878 triggered the Colorado Silver Boom.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Sherman Silver Purchase Act of 1890 invigorated silver mining, and Colorado's last, but greatest, gold strike at Cripple Creek a few months later lured a new generation of gold seekers.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Colorado women were granted the right to vote on November 7, 1893, making Colorado the second state to grant universal suffrage and the first one by a popular vote (of Colorado men).
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The repeal of the Sherman Silver Purchase Act in 1893 led to a staggering collapse of the mining and agricultural economy of Colorado, but the state slowly and steadily recovered.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Between the 1880s and 1930s, Denver's floriculture industry developed into a major industry in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] This period became known locally as the Carnation Gold Rush.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Both the 1913–1914 Coalfield War and the Denver streetcar strike of 1920 resulted in federal troops intervening to end the violence.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In 1927, the 1927-28 Colorado coal strike occurred and was ultimately successful in winning a dollar a day increase in wages.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] During it however the Columbine Mine massacre resulted in six dead strikers following a confrontation with Colorado Rangers.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In a separate incident in Trinidad the mayor was accused of deputizing members of the KKK against the striking workers.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] More than 5,000 Colorado miners—many immigrants—are estimated to have died in accidents since records were first formally collected following an 1884 accident in Crested Butte that killed 59.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In 1924, the Ku Klux Klan Colorado Realm achieved dominance in Colorado politics.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] With peak membership levels, the Second Klan levied significant control over both the local and state Democrat and Republican parties, particularly in the governor's office and city governments of Denver, Cañon City, and Durango.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] A particularly strong element of the Klan controlled the Denver Police.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Cross burnings became semi-regular occurrences in cities such as Florence and Pueblo.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Klan targeted African-Americans, Catholics, Eastern European immigrants, and other non-White Protestant groups.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Efforts by non-Klan lawmen and lawyers including Philip Van Cise led to a rapid decline in the organization's power, with membership waning significantly by the end of the 1920s.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Colorado became the first western state to host a major political convention when the Democratic Party met in Denver in 1908.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] By the U.S. census in 1930, the population of Colorado first exceeded one million residents.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Colorado suffered greatly through the Great Depression and the Dust Bowl of the 1930s, but a major wave of immigration following World War II boosted Colorado's fortune.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Tourism became a mainstay of the state economy, and high technology became an important economic engine.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The United States Census Bureau estimated that the population of Colorado exceeded five million in 2009.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] On September 11, 1957, a plutonium fire occurred at the Rocky Flats Plant, which resulted in the significant plutonium contamination of surrounding populated areas.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] From the 1940s and 1970s, many protest movements gained momentum in Colorado, predominantly in Denver.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] This included the Chicano Movement, a civil rights, and social movement of Mexican Americans emphasizing a Chicano identity that is widely considered to have begun in Denver.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The National Chicano Youth Liberation Conference was held in Colorado in March 1969.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In 1967, Colorado was the first state to loosen restrictions on abortion when governor John Love signed a law allowing abortions in cases of rape, incest, or threats to the woman's mental or physical health.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Many states followed Colorado's lead in loosening abortion laws in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Since the late 1990s, Colorado has been the site of multiple major mass shootings, including the Columbine High School massacre in 1999, where high school senior students Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold killed 13 students and one teacher, before committing suicide.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The incident made international news, and has since spawned many copycat incidents, known as the Columbine effect.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] On July 20, 2012, a gunman killed 12 people in a movie theater in Aurora.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The state responded with tighter restrictions on firearms, including introducing a limit on magazine capacity.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] On March 22, 2021, a gunman killed 10 people, including a police officer, in a King Soopers supermarket in Boulder.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In an instance of anti-LGBT violence, a gunman killed 5 people at a nightclub in Colorado Springs during the night of November 19–20, 2022.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Navy have been named the USS *Colorado*.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The first USS *Colorado* was named for the Colorado River and served in the Civil War and later the Asiatic Squadron, where it was attacked during the 1871 Korean Expedition.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The later three ships were named in honor of the state, including an armored cruiser and the battleship USS *Colorado*, the latter of which was the lead ship of her class and served in World War II in the Pacific beginning in 1941.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] At the time of the attack on Pearl Harbor, the battleship USS *Colorado* was located at the naval base in San Diego, California, and thus went unscathed.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The most recent vessel to bear the name USS *Colorado* is Virginia-class submarine USS *Colorado* (SSN-788), which was commissioned in 2018.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Colorado is notable for its diverse geography, which includes alpine mountains, high plains, deserts with huge sand dunes, and deep canyons.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In 1861, the United States Congress defined the boundaries of the new Territory of Colorado exclusively by lines of latitude and longitude, stretching from 37°N to 41°N latitude, and from 102°02′48″W to 109°02′48″W longitude (25°W to 32°W from the Washington Meridian).
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] After 165 years of government surveys, the borders of Colorado were officially defined by 697 boundary markers and 697 straight boundary lines.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Colorado, Wyoming, and Utah are the only states that have their borders defined solely by straight boundary lines with no natural features.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The southwest corner of Colorado is the Four Corners Monument at 36°59′56″N, 109°2′43″W.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Four Corners Monument, located at the place where Colorado, New Mexico, Arizona, and Utah meet, is the only place in the United States where four states meet.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Approximately half of Colorado is flat and rolling land.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] East of the Rocky Mountains is the Colorado Eastern Plains of the High Plains, the section of the Great Plains within Colorado at elevations ranging from roughly 3,350 to 7,500 feet (1,020 to 2,290 m).
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Colorado plains are mostly prairies but also include deciduous forests, buttes, and canyons.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Precipitation averages 15 to 25 inches (380 to 640 mm) annually.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Eastern Colorado is presently mainly farmland and rangeland, along with small farming villages and towns.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Corn, wheat, hay, soybeans, and oats are all typical crops.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Most villages and towns in this region boast both a water tower and a grain elevator.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Irrigation water is available from both surface and subterranean sources.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Surface water sources include the South Platte, the Arkansas River, and a few other streams.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Subterranean water is generally accessed through artesian wells.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Heavy usage of these wells for irrigation purposes caused underground water reserves to decline in the region.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Eastern Colorado also hosts a considerable amount and range of livestock, such as cattle ranches and hog farms.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] About 84% of Colorado's population resides along the eastern edge of the Rocky Mountains in the Front Range Urban Corridor between Cheyenne, Wyoming, and Pueblo, Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] This region is partially protected from prevailing storms that blow in from the Pacific Ocean region by the high Rockies in the middle of Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The "Front Range" includes Denver, Boulder, Fort Collins, Loveland, Castle Rock, Colorado Springs, Pueblo, Greeley, and other townships and municipalities in between.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] On the other side of the Rockies, the significant population centers in western Colorado (which is known as "The Western Slope") are the cities of Grand Junction, Durango, and Montrose.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] To the west of the Great Plains of Colorado rises the eastern slope of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Notable peaks of the Rocky Mountains include Longs Peak, Mount Blue Sky, Pikes Peak, and the Spanish Peaks near Walsenburg, in southern Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] This area drains to the east and the southeast, ultimately either via the Mississippi River or the Rio Grande into the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Rocky Mountains within Colorado contain 53 true peaks and 58 named peaks that are 14,000 feet (4,267 m) or higher in elevation above sea level, known as fourteeners.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] These mountains are largely covered with trees such as conifers and aspens up to the tree line, at an elevation of about 12,000 feet (3,658 m) in southern Colorado to about 10,500 feet (3,200 m) in northern Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Above this tree line, only alpine vegetation grows.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Much of the alpine snow melts by mid-August except for a few snow-capped peaks and a few small glaciers.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Colorado Mineral Belt, stretching from the San Juan Mountains in the southwest to Boulder and Central City on the front range, contains most of the historic gold- and silver-mining districts of Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The 30 highest major summits of the Rocky Mountains of North America are all within the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The summit of Mount Elbert at 14,437.6 feet (4,400.58 m) elevation in Lake County is the highest point in Colorado and the Rocky Mountains of North America.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Colorado is the only U.S. state that lies entirely above 1,000 meters elevation.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The point where the Arikaree River flows out of Yuma County, Colorado, and into Cheyenne County, Kansas, is the lowest in Colorado at 3,317 feet (1,011 m) elevation.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] This point, which is the highest low elevation point of any state, is higher than the high elevation points of 18 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Continental Divide of the Americas extends along the most of the crest of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The area of Colorado to the west of the Continental Divide is called the Western Slope of Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] West of the Continental Divide, water flows to the southwest via the Colorado River and the Green River towards the Gulf of California.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Within the interior of the Rocky Mountains are several large parks which are high broad basins.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In the north, on the east side of the Continental Divide is the North Park of Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The North Park is drained by the North Platte River, which flows north into Wyoming and Nebraska.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Just to the south of North Park, but on the western side of the Continental Divide, is the Middle Park of Colorado, which is drained by the Colorado River.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The South Park of Colorado is the region of the headwaters of the South Platte River.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In south-central Colorado is the large San Luis Valley, where the headwaters of the Rio Grande are located.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The northern part of the valley is the San Luis Closed Basin, an endorheic basin that helped created the Great Sand Dunes.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The valley sits between the Sangre de Cristo Mountains and San Juan Mountains.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Rio Grande drains due south into New Mexico, Texas, and Mexico.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Across the Sangre de Cristo Range to the east of the San Luis Valley lies the Wet Mountain Valley.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] These basins, particularly the San Luis Valley, lie along the Rio Grande rift, a major geological formation of the Rocky Mountains, and its branches.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Western Slope of Colorado includes the western face of the Rocky Mountains and all of the area to the western border.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] This area includes several terrains and climates from alpine mountains to arid deserts.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Western Slope includes many ski resort towns in the Rocky Mountains and towns west to Utah.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] It is less populous than the Front Range but includes a large number of national parks and monuments.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The northwestern corner of Colorado is a sparsely populated region, and it contains part of the noted Dinosaur National Monument, which not only is a paleontological area, but is also a scenic area of rocky hills, canyons, arid desert, and streambeds.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Here, the Green River briefly crosses over into Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Western Slope of Colorado is drained by the Colorado River and its tributaries (primarily the Gunnison River, Green River, and the San Juan River).
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Colorado River flows through Glenwood Canyon, and then through an arid valley made up of desert from Rifle to Parachute, through the desert canyon of De Beque Canyon, and into the arid desert of Grand Valley, where the city of Grand Junction is located.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Also prominent is the Grand Mesa, which lies to the southeast of Grand Junction; the high San Juan Mountains, a rugged mountain range; and to the north and west of the San Juan Mountains, the Colorado Plateau.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Grand Junction, Colorado, at the confluence of the Colorado and Gunnison Rivers, is the largest city on the Western Slope.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Grand Junction and Durango are the only major centers of television broadcasting west of the Continental Divide in Colorado, though most mountain resort communities publish daily newspapers.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Grand Junction is located at the juncture of Interstate 70 and US 50, the only major highways in western Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Grand Junction is also along the major railroad of the Western Slope, the Union Pacific.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] This railroad also provides the tracks for Amtrak's *California Zephyr* passenger train, which crosses the Rocky Mountains between Denver and Grand Junction.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Western Slope includes multiple notable destinations in the Colorado Rocky Mountains, including Glenwood Springs, with its resort hot springs, and the ski resorts of Aspen, Breckenridge, Vail, Crested Butte, Steamboat Springs, and Telluride.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Higher education in western and southwestern Colorado includes Colorado Mesa University in Grand Junction, Western Colorado University in Gunnison, Fort Lewis College in Durango, and Colorado Mountain College campuses in Glenwood Springs and Steamboat Springs.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Four Corners Monument in the southwest corner of Colorado marks the common boundary of Colorado, New Mexico, Arizona, and Utah, the only such place in the United States.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The climate of Colorado is more complex than states outside of the Mountain States region.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Unlike most other states, southern Colorado is not always warmer than northern Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Most of Colorado is made up of mountains, foothills, high plains, and desert lands.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Mountains and surrounding valleys greatly affect the local climate.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Northeast, east, and southeast Colorado are mostly the high plains, while Northern Colorado is a mix of high plains, foothills, and mountains.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Northwest and west Colorado are predominantly mountainous, with some desert lands mixed in.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Southwest and southern Colorado are a complex mixture of desert and mountain areas.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The climate of the Eastern Plains is semi-arid (Köppen climate classification: *BSk*) with low humidity and moderate precipitation, usually from 15 to 25 inches (380 to 640 mm) annually, although many areas near the rivers are semi-humid climate.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The area is known for its abundant sunshine and cool, clear nights, which give this area a great average diurnal temperature range.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The difference between the highs of the days and the lows of the nights can be considerable as warmth dissipates to space during clear nights, the heat radiation not being trapped by clouds.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Front Range urban corridor, where most of the population of Colorado resides, lies in a pronounced precipitation shadow as a result of being on the lee side of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In summer, this area can have many days above 95 °F (35 °C) and often 100 °F (38 °C).
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] On the plains, the winter lows usually range from 25 to −10 °F (−4 to −23 °C).
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] About 75% of the precipitation falls within the growing season, from April to September, but this area is very prone to droughts.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Most of the precipitation comes from thunderstorms, which can be severe, and from major snowstorms that occur in the winter and early spring.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Otherwise, winters tend to be mostly dry and cold.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In much of the region, March is the snowiest month.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] April and May are normally the rainiest months, while April is the wettest month overall.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Front Range cities closer to the mountains tend to be warmer in the winter due to Chinook winds which warm the area, sometimes bringing temperatures of 70 °F (21 °C) or higher in the winter.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The average July temperature is 55 °F (13 °C) in the morning and 90 °F (32 °C) in the afternoon.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The average January temperature is 18 °F (−8 °C) in the morning and 48 °F (9 °C) in the afternoon, although variation between consecutive days can be 40 °F (4 °C).
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Just west of the plains and into the foothills, there is a wide variety of climate types.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Locations merely a few miles apart can experience entirely different weather depending on the topography.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Most valleys have a semi-arid climate, not unlike the eastern plains, which transitions to an alpine climate at the highest elevations.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Microclimates also exist in local areas that run nearly the entire spectrum of climates, including subtropical highland (*Cfb/Cwb*), humid subtropical (*Cfa*), humid continental (*Dfa/Dfb*), Mediterranean (*Csa/Csb*) and subarctic (*Dfc*).
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Extreme weather changes are common in Colorado, although a significant portion of the extreme weather occurs in the least populated areas of the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Thunderstorms are common east of the Continental Divide in the spring and summer, yet are usually brief.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Hail is a common sight in the mountains east of the Divide and across the eastern Plains, especially the northeast part of the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Hail is the most commonly reported warm-season severe weather hazard, and occasionally causes human injuries, as well as significant property damage.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The eastern Plains are subject to some of the biggest hail storms in North America.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Notable examples are the severe hailstorms that hit Denver on July 11, 1990, and May 8, 2017, the latter being the costliest ever in the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Eastern Plains are part of the extreme western portion of Tornado Alley; some damaging tornadoes in the Eastern Plains include the 1990 Limon F3 tornado and the 2008 Windsor EF3 tornado, which devastated a small town.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Portions of the eastern Plains see especially frequent tornadoes, both those spawned from mesocyclones in supercell thunderstorms and from less intense landspouts, such as within the Denver convergence vorticity zone (DCVZ).
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The Plains are also susceptible to occasional floods and particularly severe flash floods, which are caused both by thunderstorms and by the rapid melting of snow in the mountains during warm weather.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Notable examples include the 1965 Denver Flood, the Big Thompson River flooding of 1976 and the 2013 Colorado floods.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Hot weather is common during summers in Denver.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The city's record in 1901 for the number of consecutive days above 90 °F (32 °C) was broken during the summer of 2008.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The new record of 24 consecutive days surpassed the previous record by almost a week.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Much of Colorado is very dry, with the state averaging only 17 inches (430 mm) of precipitation per year statewide.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The state rarely experiences a time when some portion is not in some degree of drought.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The lack of precipitation contributes to the severity of wildfires in the state, such as the Hayman Fire of 2002.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Other notable fires include the Fourmile Canyon Fire of 2010, the Waldo Canyon Fire and High Park Fire of June 2012, and the Black Forest Fire of June 2013.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Even these fires were exceeded in severity by the Pine Gulch Fire, Cameron Peak Fire, and East Troublesome Fire in 2020, all being the three largest fires in Colorado history (see 2020 Colorado wildfires).
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] And the Marshall Fire which started on December 30, 2021, while not the largest in state history, was the most destructive ever in terms of property loss (see Marshall Fire).
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] However, some of the mountainous regions of Colorado receive a huge amount of moisture from winter snowfalls.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The spring melts of these snows often cause great waterflows in the Yampa River, the Colorado River, the Rio Grande, the Arkansas River, the North Platte River, and the South Platte River.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Water flowing out of the Colorado Rocky Mountains is a very significant source of water for the farms, towns, and cities of the southwest states of New Mexico, Arizona, Utah, and Nevada, as well as the Midwest, such as Nebraska and Kansas, and the southern states of Oklahoma and Texas.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] A significant amount of water is also diverted for use in California; occasionally (formerly naturally and consistently), the flow of water reaches northern Mexico.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Climate change in Colorado encompasses the effects of climate change, attributed to man-made increases in atmospheric greenhouse gases, in the U.S. state of Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In 2019 *The Denver Post* reported that "[i]ndividuals living in southeastern Colorado are more vulnerable to potential health effects from climate change than residents in other parts of the state".
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Most of the state has warmed one or two degrees (F) in the last century.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Throughout the western United States, heat waves are becoming more common, snow is melting earlier in spring, and less water flows through the Colorado River.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Rising temperatures and recent droughts in the region have killed many trees by drying out soils, increasing the risk of forest fires, or enabling outbreaks of forest insects.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In the coming decades, the changing climate is likely to decrease water availability and agricultural yields in Colorado, and further increase the risk of wildfires".
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The highest official ambient air temperature ever recorded in Colorado was 115 °F (46.1 °C) on July 20, 2019, at John Martin Dam.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The lowest official air temperature was −61 °F (−51.7 °C) on February 1, 1985, at Maybell.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Despite its mountainous terrain, Colorado experiences less seismic activity than states like California and Alaska.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] There are over 90 potentially active faults, and since 1867, Colorado has experienced 700 recorded earthquakes of magnitude 2.5 or higher.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] National Earthquake Information Center is located in Golden.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] On August 22, 2011, a 5.3 magnitude earthquake occurred 9 miles (14 km) west-southwest of the city of Trinidad.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] There were no casualties and only a small amount of damage was reported.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] It was the second-largest earthquake in Colorado's history, the largest being a magnitude 6.6 earthquake, recorded in 1882.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Four minor earthquakes rattled Colorado on August 24, 2018, ranging from magnitude 2.9 to 4.3.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] As of June 2020, there were 525 recorded earthquakes in Colorado since 1973, a majority of which range 2 to 3.5 on the Richter scale.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] A process of extirpation by trapping and poisoning of the gray wolf (*Canis lupus*) from Colorado in the 1930s saw the last wild wolf in the state shot in 1945.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] A wolf pack recolonized Moffat County, Colorado in northwestern Colorado in 2019.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Cattle farmers have expressed concern that a returning wolf population potentially threatens their herds.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Coloradans voted to reintroduce gray wolves in 2020, with the state committing to a plan to have a population in the state by 2022 and permitting non-lethal methods of driving off wolves attacking livestock and pets.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Despite being an artificially-introduced species, the state declared mountain goats a native species in 1993.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] In 2013, 2014, and 2019, an unknown illness killed nearly all mountain goat kids, leading to a Colorado Parks and Wildlife investigation.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The native population of pronghorn in Colorado has varied wildly over the last century, reaching a low of only 15,000 individuals during the 1960s.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] However, conservation efforts succeeded in bringing the stable population back up to roughly 66,000 by 2013.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The population was estimated to have reached 85,000 by 2019 and had increasingly more run-ins with the increased suburban housing along the eastern Front Range.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] State wildlife officials suggested that landowners would need to modify fencing to allow the greater number of pronghorns to move unabated through the newly developed land.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Pronghorns are most readily found in the northern and eastern portions of the state, with some populations also in the western San Juan Mountains.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] Common wildlife found in the mountains of Colorado include mule deer, southwestern red squirrel, golden-mantled ground squirrel, yellow-bellied marmot, moose, American pika, and red fox, all at exceptionally high numbers, though moose are not native to the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The foothills include deer, fox squirrel, desert cottontail, mountain cottontail, and coyote.
[src:colorado/colorado-p01] The prairies are home to black-tailed prairie dog, the endangered swift fox, American badger, and white-tailed jackrabbit.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Like the federal government and all other U.S. states, Colorado's state constitution provides for three branches of government: the legislative, the executive, and the judicial branches.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The Governor of Colorado heads the state's executive branch.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The current governor is Jared Polis, a Democrat.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado's other statewide elected executive officers are the Lieutenant Governor of Colorado (elected on a ticket with the Governor), Secretary of State of Colorado, Colorado State Treasurer, and Attorney General of Colorado, all of whom serve four-year terms.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The seven-member Colorado Supreme Court is the state's highest court.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The Colorado Court of Appeals, with 22 judges, sits in divisions of three judges each.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado is divided into 23 judicial districts, each of which has a district court and a county court with limited jurisdiction.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The state also has specialized water courts, which sit in seven distinct divisions around the state and which decide matters relating to water rights and the use and administration of water.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The state legislative body is the Colorado General Assembly, which is made up of two houses – the House of Representatives and the Senate.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The House has 65 members and the Senate has 35.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] As of April 2026, the Democratic Party holds a 23 to 12 majority in the Senate and a 43 to 22 majority in the House.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] State sales taxes and many state-collected local sales taxes are administered and collected by the Colorado Department of Revenue.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado was once considered a swing state, but has become a relatively safe blue state in both state and federal elections since the late 2010s.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In presidential elections, it had not been won until 2020 by double digits since 1984 and has backed the winning candidate in 9 of the last 11 elections.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Coloradans have elected 17 Democrats and 12 Republicans to the governorship in the last 100 years.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In presidential politics, Colorado was considered a reliably Republican state during the post-World War II era, voting for the Democratic candidate only in 1948, 1964, and 1992.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] However, it became a competitive swing state in the 1990s.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Since the mid-2000s, it has swung heavily to the Democrats, voting for Barack Obama in 2008 and 2012, Hillary Clinton in 2016, Joe Biden in 2020, and Kamala Harris in 2024.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado politics exhibits a contrast between conservative cities such as Colorado Springs and Grand Junction, and liberal cities such as Boulder and Denver.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Democrats are strongest in metropolitan Denver, the college towns of Fort Collins and Boulder, southern Colorado (including Pueblo), and several western ski resort counties.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The Republicans are strongest in the Eastern Plains, Colorado Springs, Greeley, and far Western Colorado near Grand Junction.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In a 2020 study, Colorado was ranked as the seventh easiest state for citizens to vote in.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado was the first state in the union to enact, by voter referendum, a law extending suffrage to women.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] That initiative was approved by the state's voters on November 7, 1893.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] On the November 8, 1932, ballot, Colorado approved the repeal of alcohol prohibition more than a year before the Twenty-first Amendment to the United States Constitution was ratified.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado has banned, via C.R.S. section 12-6-302, the sale of motor vehicles on Sunday since at least 1953.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 1972, Colorado voters rejected a referendum proposal to fund the 1976 Winter Olympics, which had been scheduled to be held in the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Denver had been chosen by the International Olympic Committee as the host city on May 12, 1970.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Supreme Court found that preventing protected status based upon homosexuality or bisexuality did not satisfy the Equal Protection Clause.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 2006, voters passed Amendment 43, which banned same-sex marriage in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] That initiative was nullified by the U.S.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Supreme Court's 2015 decision in *Obergefell v.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 2024, Colorado residents voted to establish an explicit right to abortion in Colorado's state constitution and to repeal Amendment 43's defunct marriage ban.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 2012, voters amended the state constitution protecting the "personal use" of marijuana for adults, establishing a framework to regulate cannabis like alcohol.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The first recreational marijuana shops in Colorado, and by extension the United States, opened their doors on January 1, 2014.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] On October 30, 2019, Colorado became the first state to accept digital ID via its myColorado app.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The state-issued digital identifications will be considered valid when Real ID enforcement begins in 2025, in line with the Real ID Act of 2005.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] By November 2022 The Colorado Governor's Office of Information Technology announced that the myColorado app had over 1 million users.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] On December 19, 2023, the Colorado Supreme Court ruled that Donald Trump was disqualified from the 2024 United States presidential election in part due to his alleged incitement of the January 6 United States Capitol attack.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] On March 4, 2024, the United States Supreme Court overruled the Colorado decision.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The State of Colorado is divided into 64 counties.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Two of these counties, the City and County of Broomfield and the City and County of Denver, have consolidated city and county governments.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Counties are important units of government in Colorado since there are no civil townships or other minor civil divisions.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The most populous county in Colorado is El Paso County, the home of the City of Colorado Springs.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The second most populous county is the City and County of Denver, the state capital.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Five of the 64 counties now have more than 500,000 residents, while 12 have fewer than 5,000 residents.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The ten most populous Colorado counties are all located in the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Mesa County is the most populous county on the Colorado Western Slope.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The least populous Colorado county is Hinsdale County with 747 residents.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado has 273 active incorporated municipalities, comprising 198 towns, 73 cities, and two consolidated city and county governments.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] At the 2020 United States census, 4,299,942 of the 5,773,714 Colorado residents (74.47%) lived in one of these municipalities.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Another 714,417 residents (12.37%) lived in one of the 210 census-designated places, while the remaining 759,355 residents (13.15%) lived in the many rural and mountainous areas of the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado municipalities operate under one of five types of municipal governing authority.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado currently has two consolidated city and county governments, 61 home rule cities, 12 statutory cities, 35 home rule towns, 161 statutory towns, and one territorial charter municipality.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The most populous municipality is the City and County of Denver.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado has 12 municipalities with more than 100,000 residents, and 17 with fewer than 100 residents.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The 16 most populous Colorado municipalities are all located in the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The City of Grand Junction is the most populous municipality on the Colorado Western Slope.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The Town of Carbonate has had no year-round population since the 1890 census due to its severe winter weather and difficult access.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In addition to its 272 municipalities, Colorado has 210 unincorporated census-designated places (CDPs) and many other small communities.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The most populous unincorporated community in Colorado is Highlands Ranch south of Denver.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The seven most populous CDPs are located in the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The Clifton CDP is the most populous CDP on the Colorado Western Slope.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado has more than 4,000 special districts, most with property tax authority.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] These districts may provide health services, ambulance, schools, law enforcement, fire protection, water, sewage, drainage, irrigation, transportation, recreation, infrastructure, cultural facilities, business support, redevelopment, or other services.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Some of these districts have the authority to levy sales tax as well as property tax and use fees.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The 17 core-based statistical areas in the U.S.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Most recently on July 21, 2023, the Office of Management and Budget defined 21 statistical areas for Colorado comprising four combined statistical areas, seven metropolitan statistical areas, and ten micropolitan statistical areas.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The most populous of the seven metropolitan statistical areas in Colorado is the 10-county Denver–Aurora–Centennial, CO Metropolitan Statistical Area with a population of 2,963,821 at the 2020 United States census, an increase of +15.29% since the 2010 census.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The more extensive 12-county Denver–Aurora–Greeley, CO Combined Statistical Area had a population of 3,623,560 at the 2020 census, an increase of +17.23% since the 2010 census.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The most populous extended metropolitan region in Rocky Mountain Region is the 18-county Front Range Urban Corridor along the northeast face of the Southern Rocky Mountains.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] This region with Denver at its center had a population of 5,055,344 at the 2020 census, an increase of +16.65% since the 2010 census.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The United States Census Bureau estimated the population of Colorado on July 1, 2024, at 5,957,493, a 3.2% increase since the 2020 United States census.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Coloradan Hispanics and Latinos (of any race and heritage) made up 20.7% of the population.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] According to the 2000 census, the largest ancestry groups in Colorado are German (22%), Mexican (18%), Irish (12%), and English (12%).
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Persons reporting German ancestry are especially numerous in the Front Range, the Rockies (west-central counties), and Eastern parts/High Plains.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado has a high proportion of Hispanic, mostly Mexican-American, citizens in Metropolitan Denver, Colorado Springs, as well as the smaller cities of Greeley and Pueblo, and elsewhere.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Southern, Southwestern, and Southeastern Colorado have a large number of Hispanos, the descendants of the early settlers of colonial Spanish origin.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Census Bureau reported Colorado's population as 8.2% Hispanic and 90.3% non-Hispanic White.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The Hispanic population of Colorado has continued to grow quickly over the past decades.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] By 2019, Hispanics made up 22% of Colorado's population, and Non-Hispanic Whites made up 70%.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Spoken English in Colorado has many Spanish idioms.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado also has some large African-American communities located in Denver, in the neighborhoods of Montbello, Five Points, Whittier, and many other East Denver areas.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In the 2020 Census, 234,828 Colorado residents were identified as African American (of the total 5,773,714).
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Arapahoe, at 10.8% African American, was the only one of the state's 64 counties where African Americans make up more than 10% of the population.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] African Americans in the seven counties of Arapahoe (70,787), Denver (64,038), El Paso (43,822), Adams (17,463), Jefferson (7,356), Douglas (5,160), and Weld (4,539) make up more than 90% of all African Americans in the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The population of Native Americans in the state is small.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Native Americans are concentrated in metropolitan Denver and the southwestern corner of Colorado, where there are two Ute reservations.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The majority of Colorado's immigrants are from Mexico, India, China, Vietnam, Korea, Germany and Canada.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] There were a total of 70,331 births in Colorado in 2006.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] (Birth rate of 14.6 per thousand.) In 2007, non-Hispanic Whites were involved in 59.1% of all births.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Some 14.06% of those births involved a non-Hispanic White person and someone of a different race, most often with a couple including one Hispanic.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] A birth where at least one Hispanic person was involved counted for 43% of the births in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Per the 2000 census, the Hispanic population is estimated to be 918,899, or approximately 20% of the state's total population.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado has the 5th-largest population of Mexican-Americans, behind California, Texas, Arizona, and Illinois.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In percentages, Colorado has the 6th-highest percentage of Mexican-Americans, behind New Mexico, California, Texas, Arizona, and Nevada.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 2011, 46% of Colorado's population younger than the age of one were minorities, meaning that they had at least one parent who was not non-Hispanic White.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 2017, Colorado recorded the second-lowest fertility rate in the United States outside of New England, after Oregon, at 1.63 children per woman.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Significant contributing factors to the decline in pregnancies were the Title X Family Planning Program and an intrauterine device grant from Warren Buffett's family.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] English, the official language of the state, is the most commonly spoken language in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The second most commonly spoken language in the state is Spanish.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The Colorado River Numic language, also known as the Ute dialect, is still spoken in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Major religious affiliations of the people of Colorado as of 2014 were 64% Christian, of whom there are 44% Protestant, 16% Roman Catholic, 3% Mormon, and 1% Eastern Orthodox.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Other religious breakdowns according to the Pew Research Center were 1% Judaism, 1% Muslim, 1% Buddhist, and 4% other.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Secular Coloradans made up 29% of the population.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 2020, according to the Public Religion Research Institute, Christianity was 66% of the population.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Judaism was also reported to have increased in this separate study, forming 2% of the religious landscape, while the religiously unaffiliated were reported to form 28% of the population in this separate study.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 2022, the same organization reported 61% was Christian (39% Protestant, 19% Catholic, 2% Mormon, 1% Eastern Orthodox), 2% New Age, 1% Jewish, 1% Hindu, and 34% religiously unaffiliated.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] According to the Association of Religion Data Archives, the largest Christian denominations by the number of adherents in 2010 were the Catholic Church with 811,630; multi-denominational Evangelical Protestants with 229,981; and the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 151,433.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 2020, the Association of Religion Data Archives determined the largest Christian denominations were Catholics (873,236), non/multi/inter-denominational Protestants (406,798), and Mormons (150,509).
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Throughout its non-Christian population, there were 12,500 Hindus, 7,101 Hindu Yogis, and 17,369 Buddhists at the 2020 study.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Our Lady of Guadalupe Catholic Church was the first permanent Catholic parish in modern-day Colorado and was constructed by Spanish colonists from New Mexico in modern-day Conejos.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Latin Church Catholics are served by three dioceses: the Archdiocese of Denver and the Dioceses of Colorado Springs and Pueblo.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The first permanent settlement by members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in Colorado arrived from Mississippi and initially camped along the Arkansas River just east of the present-day site of Pueblo.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado is generally considered among the healthiest states by behavioral and healthcare researchers.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Among the positive contributing factors is the state's well-known outdoor recreation opportunities and initiatives.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] However, there is a stratification of health metrics with wealthier counties such as Douglas and Pitkin performing significantly better relative to southern, less wealthy counties such as Huerfano and Las Animas.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] According to several studies, Coloradans have the lowest rates of obesity of any state in the US.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] As of 2018, 24% of the population was considered medically obese, and while the lowest in the nation, the percentage had increased from 17% in 2004.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] According to a report in the *Journal of the American Medical Association*, residents of Colorado had a 2014 life expectancy of 80.21 years, the longest of any U.S. state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 10,397 homeless people in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The number of employer establishments is 174,258.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado's gross domestic product in 2025 was $584.3 billion.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado's per capita personal income was $86,181 in 2025, ranking Colorado 10th in the nation.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Median Annual Household Income in 2016 was $70,666, 8th in the nation.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The state's economy broadened from its mid-19th-century roots in mining when irrigated agriculture developed, and by the late 19th century, raising livestock had become important.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Early industry was based on the extraction and processing of minerals and agricultural products.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Current agricultural products are cattle, wheat, dairy products, corn, and hay.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 2025, small businesses made up 99.5% of Colorado businesses, and employed 48.6% of the state's work force.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Geological Survey and other government agencies at the Denver Federal Center near Lakewood; the Denver Mint, Buckley Space Force Base, the Tenth Circuit Court of Appeals, and the Byron G.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Rogers Federal Building and United States Courthouse in Denver; and a federal Supermax Prison and other federal prisons near Cañon City.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In addition to these and other federal agencies, Colorado has abundant National Forest land and four National Parks that contribute to federal ownership of 24,615,788 acres (99,617 km2) of land in Colorado, or 37% of the total area of the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In the second half of the 20th century, the industrial and service sectors expanded greatly.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The state's economy is diversified and is notable for its concentration on scientific research and high-technology industries.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Other industries include food processing, transportation equipment, machinery, chemical products, the extraction of metals such as gold (see Gold mining in Colorado), silver, and molybdenum.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado now also has the largest annual production of beer in any state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Denver is an important financial center.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The state's diverse geography and majestic mountains attract millions of tourists every year, including 85.2 million in 2018.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Tourism contributes greatly to Colorado's economy, with tourists generating $22.3 billion in 2018.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Several nationally known brand names have originated in Colorado factories and laboratories.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] From Denver came the forerunner of telecommunications giant Qwest in 1879, Samsonite luggage in 1910, Gates belts and hoses in 1911, and Russell Stover Candies in 1923.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Kuner canned vegetables began in Brighton in 1864.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] From Golden came Coors beer in 1873, CoorsTek industrial ceramics in 1920, and Jolly Rancher candy in 1949.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] CF&I railroad rails, wire, nails, and pipe debuted in Pueblo in 1892.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Holly Sugar was first milled from beets in Holly in 1905, and later moved its headquarters to Colorado Springs.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The present-day Swift packed meat of Greeley evolved from Monfort of Colorado, Inc., established in 1930.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Estes model rockets were launched in Penrose in 1958.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Fort Collins has been the home of Woodward Governor Company's motor controllers (governors) since 1870, and Waterpik dental water jets and showerheads since 1962.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Celestial Seasonings herbal teas have been made in Boulder since 1969.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Rocky Mountain Chocolate Factory made its first candy in Durango in 1981.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado has a flat 4.63% income tax, regardless of income level.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] On November 3, 2020, voters authorized an initiative to lower that income tax rate to 4.55 percent.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Unlike most states, which calculate taxes based on federal *adjusted gross income*, Colorado taxes are based on *taxable income*—income after federal exemptions and federal itemized (or standard) deductions.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado's state sales tax is 2.9% on retail sales.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] When state revenues exceed state constitutional limits, according to Colorado's Taxpayer Bill of Rights legislation, full-year Colorado residents can claim a sales tax refund on their individual state income tax return.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Many counties and cities charge their own rates, in addition to the base state rate.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] There are also certain county and special district taxes that may apply.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Real estate and personal business property are taxable in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The state's senior property tax exemption was temporarily suspended by the Colorado Legislature in 2003.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The tax break was scheduled to return for the assessment year 2006, payable in 2007.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] As of May 2025, the state's unemployment rate was 4.8%.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The West Virginia teachers' strike in 2018 inspired teachers in other states, including Colorado, to take similar action.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Corn is grown in the Eastern Plains of Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Arid conditions and drought negatively impacted yields in 2020 and 2022.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado has significant hydrocarbon resources.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] According to the Energy Information Administration, Colorado hosts seven of the largest natural gas fields in the United States, and two of the largest oil fields.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Conventional and unconventional natural gas output from several Colorado basins typically accounts for more than five percent of annual U.S. natural gas production.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado's oil shale deposits hold an estimated 1 trillion barrels (160 km3) of oil—nearly as much oil as the entire world's proven oil reserves.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Substantial deposits of bituminous, subbituminous, and lignite coal are found in the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Uranium mining in Colorado goes back to 1872, when pitchblende ore was taken from gold mines near Central City, Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Not counting byproduct uranium from phosphate, Colorado is considered to have the third-largest uranium reserves of any U.S. state, behind Wyoming and New Mexico.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] When Colorado and Utah dominated radium mining from 1910 to 1922, uranium and vanadium were the byproducts (giving towns like present-day Superfund site Uravan their names).
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Uranium price increases from 2001 to 2007 prompted several companies to revive uranium mining in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] During the 1940s certain communities–including Naturita and Paradox–earned the moniker of "yellowcake towns" from their relationship with uranium mining.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Price drops and financing problems in late 2008 forced these companies to cancel or scale back the uranium-mining project.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] As of 2016, there were no major uranium mining operations in the state, though plans existed to restart production.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado's high Rocky Mountain ridges and eastern plains offer wind power potential, and geologic activity in the mountain areas provides the potential for geothermal power development.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Much of the state is sunny and could produce solar power.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Major rivers flowing from the Rocky Mountains offer hydroelectric power resources.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Several film productions have been shot on location in Colorado, especially prominent Westerns like *True Grit*, *The Searchers*, *City Slickers,* *Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid, and My Life With the Walter Boys*.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Several historic military forts, railways with trains still operating, and mining ghost towns have been used and transformed for historical accuracy in well-known films.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] There are also several scenic highways and mountain passes that helped to feature the open road in films such as *Vanishing Point*, *Bingo* and *Starman*.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Some Colorado landmarks have been featured in films, such as The Stanley Hotel in *Dumb and Dumber* and *The Shining* and the Sculptured House in *Sleeper*.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 2015, *Furious 7* was to film driving sequences on Pikes Peak Highway in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The TV adult-animated series *South Park* takes place in central Colorado in the titular town.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Additionally, the TV series *Good Luck Charlie* was set, but not filmed, in Denver, Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The Colorado Office of Film and Television has noted that more than 400 films have been shot in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] On March 27, 2025, it was announced Sundance Film Festival would move to Boulder starting in 2027 after reaching a deal for a ten-year duration.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Many notable writers have lived or spent extended periods in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] *5280*, a Denver magazine, wrote in 2015 that Kent Haruf is "widely considered [to be] Colorado's finest novelist"; Haruf set his novels in the fictional high plains Colorado town of Holt.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Beat Generation writers Jack Kerouac and Neal Cassady lived in and around Denver for several years each.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Irish playwright Oscar Wilde visited Colorado on his tour of the United States in 1882, writing in his 1906 *Impressions of America* that Leadville was "the richest city in the world.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado is known for its Southwest and Rocky Mountain cuisine, with Mexican restaurants found throughout the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Boulder was named America's Foodiest Town 2010 by Bon Appétit.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Boulder, and Colorado in general, is home to several national food and beverage companies, top-tier restaurants and farmers' markets.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Boulder also has more Master Sommeliers per capita than any other city, including San Francisco and New York.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Denver is known for steak, but now has a diverse culinary scene with many restaurants.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Polidori Sausage is a brand of pork products available in supermarkets, which originated in Colorado, in the early 20th century.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The Food & Wine Classic is held annually each June in Aspen.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Aspen also has a reputation as the culinary capital of the Rocky Mountain region.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado wines include varietals that have attracted favorable notice from outside the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] With wines made from traditional *Vitis vinifera* grapes along with wines made from cherries, peaches, plums, and honey, Colorado wines have won top national and international awards for their quality.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado's grape growing regions contain the highest elevation vineyards in the United States, with most viticulture in the state practiced between 4,000 and 7,000 feet (1,219 and 2,134 m) above sea level.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The mountain climate ensures warm summer days and cool nights.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado is home to two designated American Viticultural Areas of the Grand Valley AVA and the West Elks AVA, where most of the vineyards in the state are located.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] However, an increasing number of wineries are located along the Front Range.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 2018, Wine Enthusiast Magazine named Colorado's Grand Valley AVA in Mesa County, Colorado, as one of the Top Ten wine travel destinations in the world.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado is home to many nationally praised microbreweries, including New Belgium Brewing Company, Odell Brewing Company, and Great Divide Brewing Company.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The area of northern Colorado near and between the cities of Denver, Boulder, and Fort Collins is known as the "Napa Valley of Beer" due to its high density of craft breweries.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado is open to cannabis (marijuana) tourism.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] With the adoption of the 64th state amendment in 2012, Colorado became the first state in the union to legalize marijuana for medicinal (2000), industrial (referring to hemp, 2012), and recreational (2012) use.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado's marijuana industry sold $1.31 billion worth of marijuana in 2016 and $1.26 billion in the first three-quarters of 2017.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The state generated tax, fee, and license revenue of $194 million in 2016 on legal marijuana sales.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado regulates hemp as any part of the plant with less than 0.3% THC.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] On April 4, 2014, Senate Bill 14–184 addressing oversight of Colorado's industrial hemp program was first introduced, ultimately being signed into law by Governor John Hickenlooper on May 31, 2014.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] On November 7, 2000, 54% of Colorado voters passed Amendment 20, which amends the Colorado State constitution to allow the medical use of marijuana.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Currently, Colorado has listed "eight medical conditions for which patients can use marijuana—cancer, glaucoma, HIV/AIDS, muscle spasms, seizures, severe pain, severe nausea and cachexia, or dramatic weight loss and muscle atrophy".
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] While governor, John Hickenlooper allocated about half of the state's $13 million "Medical Marijuana Program Cash Fund" to medical research in the 2014 budget.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] By 2018, the Medical Marijuana Program Cash Fund was the "largest pool of pot money in the state" and was used to fund programs including research into pediatric applications for controlling autism symptoms.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] On November 6, 2012, voters amended the state constitution to protect "personal use" of marijuana for adults, establishing a framework to regulate marijuana in a manner similar to alcohol.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado's primary mode of transportation (in terms of passengers) is its highway system.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Interstate 25 (I-25) is the primary north–south highway in the state, connecting Pueblo, Colorado Springs, Denver, and Fort Collins, and extending north to Wyoming and south to New Mexico.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] It connects Grand Junction and the mountain communities with Denver and enters Utah and Kansas.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The state is home to a network of US and Colorado highways that provide access to all principal areas of the state.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Many smaller communities are connected to this network only via county roads.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Denver International Airport (DIA) is the third-busiest domestic U.S. and international airport in the world by passenger traffic.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] DIA handles by far the largest volume of commercial air traffic in Colorado and is the busiest U.S. hub airport between Chicago and the Pacific coast, making Denver the most important airport for connecting passenger traffic in the western United States.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Public transportation bus services are offered both intra-city and inter-city—including the Denver metro area's RTD services.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The Regional Transportation District (RTD) operates the popular RTD Bus & Rail transit system in the Denver Metropolitan Area.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] As of January 2013 the RTD rail system had 170 light-rail vehicles, serving 47 miles (76 km) of track.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In addition to local public transit, intercity bus service is provided by Burlington Trailways, Bustang and Greyhound Lines.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Amtrak operates two passenger rail lines in Colorado, the *California Zephyr* and *Southwest Chief*.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado's contribution to world railroad history was forged principally by the Denver and Rio Grande Western Railroad which began in 1870 and wrote the book on mountain railroading.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 1988 the "Rio Grande" was acquired, but was merged into, the Southern Pacific Railroad by their joint owner Philip Anschutz.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] On September 11, 1996, Anschutz sold the combined company to the Union Pacific Railroad, creating the largest railroad network in the United States.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The Anschutz sale was partly in response to the earlier merger of Burlington Northern and Santa Fe which formed the large Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railway (BNSF), Union Pacific's principal competitor in western U.S. railroading.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Both Union Pacific and BNSF have extensive freight operations in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Colorado's freight railroad network consists of 2,688 miles of Class I trackage.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] It is integral to the U.S. economy, being a critical artery for the movement of energy, agriculture, mining, and industrial commodities as well as general freight and manufactured products between the East and Midwest and the Pacific coast states.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In August 2014, Colorado began to issue driver licenses to aliens not lawfully in the United States who lived in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In September 2014, KCNC reported that 524 non-citizens were issued Colorado driver licenses that are normally issued to U.S. citizens living in Colorado.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The first institution of higher education in the Colorado Territory was the Colorado Seminary, opened on November 16, 1864, by the Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The seminary closed in 1867 but reopened in 1880 as the University of Denver.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] In 1870, the Bishop George Maxwell Randall of the Episcopal Church's Missionary District of Colorado and Parts Adjacent opened the first of what become the Colorado University Schools which would include the Territorial School of Mines opened in 1873 and sold to the Colorado Territory in 1874.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] These schools were initially run by the Episcopal Church.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] An 1861 territorial act called for the creation of a public university in Boulder, though it would not be until 1876 that the University of Colorado was founded.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The 1876 act also renamed Territorial School of Mines as the Colorado School of Mines.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] An 1870 territorial act created the Agricultural College of Colorado which opened in 1879.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The college was renamed the Colorado State College of Agriculture and Mechanic Arts in 1935, and became Colorado State University in 1957.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The first Catholic college in Colorado was the Jesuit Sacred Heart College, which was founded in New Mexico in 1877, moved to Morrison in 1884, and to Denver in 1887.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The college was renamed Regis College in 1921 and Regis University in 1991.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] On April 1, 1924, armed students patrolled the campus after a burning cross was found, the climax of tensions between Regis College and the locally-powerful Ku Klux Klan.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Following a 1950 assessment by the Service Academy Board, it was determined that there was a need to supplement the U.S.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Military and Naval Academies with a third school that would provide commissioned officers for the newly independent Air Force.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] On April 1, 1954, President Dwight Eisenhower signed a law that moved for the creation of a U.S.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] Later that year, Colorado Springs was selected to host the new institution.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] From its establishment in 1955, until the construction of appropriate facilities in Colorado Springs was completed and opened in 1958, the Air Force Academy operated out of Lowry Air Force Base in Denver.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] With the opening of the Colorado Springs facility, the cadets moved to the new campus, though not in the full-kit march that some urban and campus legends suggest.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The first class of Space Force officers from the Air Force Academy commissioned on April 18, 2020.
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The two Native American reservations remaining in Colorado are the Southern Ute Indian Reservation (1873; Ute dialect: *Kapuuta-wa Moghwachi Núuchi-u*) and Ute Mountain Ute Indian Reservation (1940; Ute dialect: *Wʉgama Núuchi*).
[src:colorado/colorado-p02] The two abolished Indian reservations in Colorado were the Cheyenne and Arapaho Indian Reservation (1851–1870) and Ute Indian Reservation (1855–1873).
[src:colorado/colorado-p03] Colorado has five major professional sports leagues, all based in the Denver metropolitan area.
[src:colorado/colorado-p03] Colorado is the least populous state with a franchise in each of the major professional sports leagues.
[src:colorado/colorado-p03] The Pikes Peak International Hill Climb is a major hill climbing motor race held on the Pikes Peak Highway.
[src:colorado/colorado-p03] The Cherry Hills Country Club has hosted several professional golf tournaments, including the U.S.
[src:colorado/colorado-p03] Women's Open, PGA Championship and BMW Championship.
[src:colorado/colorado-p03] The following universities and colleges participate in the National Collegiate Athletic Association Division I.
